y = 3 ** x
z = 5 - (y * 2)

Intro to Numpy#

Materials adapted from Software Carpentries Programming with Python Workshop (CC-BY 4.0).

Set-up

Our imaginary colleague â€œDr. Maverickâ€ has invented a new miracle drug that promises to cure arthritis inflammation flare-ups after only 3 weeks since initially taking the medication! Naturally, we wish to see the clinical trial data, and after months of asking for the data they have finally provided us with a CSV spreadsheet containing the clinical trial data.

The CSV file contains the number of inflammation flare-ups per day for the 60 patients in the initial clinical trial, with the trial lasting 40 days. Each row corresponds to a patient, and each column corresponds to a day in the trial. Once a patient has their first inflammation flare-up they take the medication and wait a few weeks for it to take effect and reduce flare-ups.

What are some things we might want to look at about this data?

What are libraries?#

In Python, there is a relatively small amount of core code (whatâ€™s present in this notebook by default). To get more advanced functionality, we need to import libraries.

What are arrays?#

We want to be able to work with more than one data point so we need arrays.

To work with arrays, we will use the numpy library, which is a core library for scientific computing

NumPy = Numerical Python

We import numpy as follows

import numpy as np

# Really weird code that you shouldn't worry about for now

import requests
import io

r = requests.get('https://osf.io/vztk7/download')

data = np.loadtxt(io.BytesIO(r.content), delimiter=',')


print(data)

Vectorization#

If you do something like a math operation on an array, it will do element-wise operation

import numpy as np
x = np.array([[1, 0, 1], [3, 4, 1]])

x + 1

array([[2, 1, 2],
       [4, 5, 2]])

If we do something like added two arrays of the same shape, that will also be element-wise.

y = np.array([[2, 3, 0], [4, 1, 1]])

x + y

array([[3, 3, 1],
       [7, 5, 2]])

Intro to Plotting#

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

ave_inflammation = np.mean(data, axis=0)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.plot(ave_inflammation)

ax.set(xlabel = 'Days',
       ylabel = 'Average Inflammation')

[Text(0.5, 0, 'Days'), Text(0, 0.5, 'Average Inflammation')]

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.plot(ave_inflammation, 'o')

ax.set(xlabel = 'Days',
       ylabel = 'Average Inflammation')

[Text(0.5, 0, 'Days'), Text(0, 0.5, 'Average Inflammation')]

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

img = ax.imshow(data)

plt.colorbar(img)

ax.set(xlabel='Days',
       ylabel = 'Patients')

[Text(0.5, 0, 'Days'), Text(0, 0.5, 'Patients')]
